title: Neutron Cross-Section Measurements of 12C between 14 and 25 MeV

x4freetext: Neutron Cross-Section Measurements of 12C between 14
and 25 MeV

x4freetext: T(d,n) reaction, deuterons of 2 different energies as
given in subentries. The fast
neutrons in the present measurements were obtained by
bombarding a titanium tritide target with deuterons
from the 4-MeV Van de Graaff accelerator of The
University of Texas for the range 14 to 21 MeV, and
from the tandem accelerator in the energy range above
21 MeV.
A spherical shell of pure graphite
of 6-in. o.d. and 3-in. i.d.
The neutron detector, a cylinder of
stilbene 1 in. in length and 1 in. in diameter. The
gamma-ray measurements were made with a 2x2-in. NaI
crystal.
For each neutron energy, measurements were made
with the four geometrical arrangements. The
recoil spectra obtained under these conditions were
collected.  Taking the midpoint of the slope at the
end of the spectrum as representative of the energy
of the neutrons responsible for the proton recoil
spectrum, a calibration curve of neutron energy
against channel number was plotted. Differential
elastic scattering measurements were made at angles
which would correspond to the emission of neutrons
in the center-of-mass system at angles near the zeros
of the first four Legendre polynomials (90,54.8,39.2,
and 30.5 degrees).
The proton recoil spectra obtained in the
four geometrical arrangements allow the following
four determinations of the number of neutrons
reaching the detector: (A) without shadow cone or
scatterer, (B) with the shadow cone shielding the
detector, (C) with the scatterer surrounding the
shielded detector, and (D) with the scatterer in
position without the shadow cone. The quantity
(C minus B)/(A minus B), the fraction of the neutrons
scattered and (A minus D)/(A minus B) the nonelastic
scattering, were determined.
Absolute cross sections were
therefore obtained using the known absolute
differential cross sections at 14 MeV. The geometrical
arrangement is not conducive to making absolute
measurements because the mean thickness of material
between the detector and any point where a neutron is
scattered is too great to make an approximate
calculation worthwhile.
Correction for contributions caused by neutrons
produced by deuterium. The neutron fluxes from both
tritium and deuterium targets were measured and the
yield of gamma-rays from the deuterium target was
obtained using the same geometry. Such corrections
were about 10%. For deuteron energies above 1.5 MeV,
neutrons emitted in the forward direction from the
D(d,n)3He reaction have sufficient energy to excite
the 4.43-MeV state in 12C by inelastic scattering
(threshold 4.80 MeV). Consequently a correction must
be made in the gamma-ray measurements made with a
tritide source for contributions caused by neutrons
produced by deuterium.
